  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7df7d550",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Introduction to CASA tools\n",
    "\n",
    "This tutorial is meant to provide an introduction to working with the `tb` and `ms` tools of CASA.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Introduction to measurement sets\n",
    "Before you begin, it's worthwhile reviewing the CASA documentation on the measurement set, which is the default storage format for radio interferometric observations. The basics are [here](https://casa.nrao.edu/casadocs-devel/stable/casa-fundamentals/the-measurementset) and the description of the v2 format is [here](https://casa.nrao.edu/casadocs-devel/stable/casa-fundamentals/measurement-set). To make a long story short, a measurement set (e.g., ``my_ALMA_data.ms``) is a folder containing a set of binary 'tables' with your data and metadata. The contents within this measurement set folder serve as a [relational database](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relational_database). It helps to keep this structure in mind as we navigate its contents.\n",
    "\n",
    "A good first task is to load up an interactive prompt of CASA and run [listobs](https://casa.nrao.edu/casadocs-devel/stable/global-task-list/task_listobs/about) to familiarize yourself with the basic structure of your measurement set. It will be very helpful to know things like how many spectral windows there are, how many execution blocks there are, and what targets were observed. Hopefully you've already [split](https://casa.nrao.edu/casadocs-devel/stable/calibration-and-visibility-data/uv-manipulation/splitting-out-calibrated-uv-data-split) out your data such that it only contains the target under consideration and does not include any extra calibrator targets. It's also a good idea to inspect and plot the visibilities of your measurement set using CASA's [plotms](https://casa.nrao.edu/casadocs-devel/stable/calibration-and-visibility-data/data-examination-and-editing/using-plotms-to-plot-and-edit-visibilities-and-calibration-tables) tool.\n",
    "\n",
    "CASA provides the [casabrowser/browsetable](https://casa.nrao.edu/casadocs-devel/stable/calibration-and-visibility-data/data-examination-and-editing/browse-a-table) tool, which is very handy for graphically exploring the structure and contents of this relational database. If something about the structure of the measurement set doesn't make sense, it's usually a good idea to open up *browsetable* and dig into the structure of the individual tables."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5d469224",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## CASA tools\n",
    "CASA provides a set of lower-level \"tools\" for direct interaction with the measurement set contents. The full API list is available [here](https://casa.nrao.edu/casadocs-devel/stable/global-tool-list).\n",
    "\n",
    "To experiment with reading and plotting visibilities, we'll use a measurement set that we prepared using simobserve. The full commands to generate the measurement set are available via the `mpoldatasets` package [here](https://github.com/MPoL-dev/mpoldatasets/blob/main/products/ALMA-logo/simobserve_cube.py).\n",
    "\n",
    "You can access the CASA tools from within your Python environment if you've successfully installed ``casatools`` package as part of the [modular CASA install](https://casa.nrao.edu/casadocs-devel/stable/usingcasa/obtaining-and-installing), as shown here. If you are unable to install the modular package, you can always use the [casatools directly inside of the monolithic CASA intepreter](https://casa.nrao.edu/casadocs-devel/stable/casa-fundamentals/tasks-and-tools). If you're working directly within the CASA interpreter, you can skip this section and move directly to the example queries."
   ]
  },

    "## Example Queries with table tools\n",
    "The following are some examples of simple queries you might like to do for a simply structured measurement set using the `tb` tool. If they don't work, you might look using the `ms` tool, described at the bottom of the page."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0939bd1c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "a10a9f97",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:17.342793Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:17.342251Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:17.369391Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:17.368830Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "[0]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "tb.open(fname)\n",
    "spw_id = tb.getcol(\"DATA_DESC_ID\")  # array of int with shape [npol, nchan, nvis]\n",
    "tb.close()\n",
    "print(np.unique(spw_id))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fd0c8f5b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

You could also try accessing the ``DATA_DESCRIPTION`` table directly by providing it as a subdirectory to the main table like so"
   ]

   "execution_count": 12,
   "id": "5546fb3a",
   "metadata": {

     "name": "stdout",

  },

    "### Convert baselines to units of kilolambda\n",
    "To convert the baselines to units of kilolambda, we need to know the observing frequency (or wavelength). For a spectral window with multiple channels (like this one), the baselines (if expressed in units of kilolambda) will be slightly different for each channel because the observing frequency is different for each channel. Here is one way to go about broadcasting the baselines to all channels and then converting them to units of kilolambda."

    "# broadcast to the same shape as the data\n",
    "# stub to broadcast uu,vv, and weights to all channels\n",
    "nchan = num_chan[0]  # grab the number of channels for the first spectral window\n",
    "broadcast = np.ones((nchan, 1))\n",
    "uu = uu * broadcast\n",
    "vv = vv * broadcast"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "code",

   "id": "34721867",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:18.243141Z",

   "source": [
    "# calculate wavelengths in meters\n",
    "c_ms = 2.99792458e8  # [m s^-1]\n",
    "wavelengths = c_ms / chan_freq[:, np.newaxis]  # m"

   "source": [
    "# convert baselines to klambda\n",

   "id": "a9cbec83",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Read the visibility values and inspect flags\n",
    "Visibilities are stored in the main table of the measurement set. As long as all spectral windows have the same number of channels and polarizations, it should be possible to read visibilities using the table tool. If not, try the `ms` tool."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 24,
   "id": "7b99efac",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.013643Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.013055Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.375852Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.376337Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "True"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 1,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "tb.open(fname)\n",
    "weight = tb.getcol(\"WEIGHT\")  # array of float64 with shape [npol, nvis]\n",
    "flag = tb.getcol(\"FLAG\")  # array of bool with shape [npol, nchan, nvis]\n",
    "data_raw = tb.getcol(\"DATA\")  # array of complex128 with shape [npol, nchan, nvis]\n",
    "data_corrected = tb.getcol(\n",
    "    \"CORRECTED_DATA\"\n",
    ")  # array of complex128 with shape [npol, nchan, nvis]\n",
    "tb.close()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "74bae495",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Depending on how you've calibrated and/or split out your data, your measurement set may or may not have a ``CORRECTED_DATA`` column. Usually, this is the one you want. If the column doesn't exist in your measurement set, try the ``DATA`` column instead.\n",
    "\n",
    "For each visibility $i$ there is also an accompanying ``WEIGHT`` $w_i$, which should correspond to the statistical uncertainty on the real and imaginary component of each visibility. Formally, the weight is defined as\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "w_i = \\frac{1}{\\sigma_i^2}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "and we expect that the noise is independent for each of the real and imaginary components of a visibility measurement. This means that we expect\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\Re \\{V_i\\} = \\Re\\{\\mathcal{V}\\}_i + \\epsilon_1\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "and\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\Im \\{V_i\\} = \\Im\\{\\mathcal{V}\\}_i + \\epsilon_2\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where for each real and each imaginary component $\\epsilon$ is a new noise realization from a mean-zero Gaussian with standard deviation $\\sigma_i$, i.e.,\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\epsilon \\sim \\mathcal{N}\\left ( 0, \\sigma_i \\right )\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "CASA has a [history](https://casa.nrao.edu/casadocs-devel/stable/calibration-and-visibility-data/data-weights) of different weight definitions, so this is definitely an important column to pay attention to, especially if your data was not acquired and processed in very recent cycles."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2867150d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A common ALMA observation mode is dual-polarization, XX and YY. If this is the case for your observations, the data array will contain an extra dimension for each polarization."
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "code",

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d8db5536",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In the process of calibrating real-world data, some occasional visibilities need to be flagged or excluded from the analysis. The ``FLAG`` column is a boolean flag that is ``True`` if the visibility *should be excluded*. To check if any visibilities are flagged in this spectral window, we can just see if there are any ``True`` values in the ``FLAG`` column"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 27,
   "id": "627f3540",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.399681Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.398695Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.401427Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.401894Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Are there any flagged visibilities? False\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "print(\"Are there any flagged visibilities?\", np.any(flag))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "de61fe17",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Since this is a simulated measurement set, this is not surprising. When you are using real data, however, this is an important thing to check. If you *did* have flagged visibilities, to access only the valid visibilities you would do something like the following"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 28,
   "id": "e305c0f7",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.405554Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.404963Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.496248Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.495656Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "data_good = data_corrected[~flag]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7d485949",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "where the ``~`` operator helps us index only the visibilities which *are not flagged*. Unfortunately, indexing en masse like this removes any polarization and channelization dimensionality, just giving you a flat list"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 29,
   "id": "f8310801",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.501550Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.500463Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.503628Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.503162Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "(5851440,)\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "print(data_good.shape)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e71bfb69",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "so you'll need to be more strategic about this if you'd like to preserve the channel dimensions, perhaps by using a masked array or a ragged list."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "df00edf5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Read visibility values and averaging polarizations\n",
    "If your dataset is dual-polarization but you are not interested in treating the polarizations separately, it might be worth it to average the polarization channels together."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 30,
   "id": "bbdce8a0",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.508073Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.507498Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.778068Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.778917Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "True"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 1,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "tb.open(fname)\n",
    "uvw = tb.getcol(\"UVW\")  # array of float64 with shape [3, nvis]\n",
    "weight = tb.getcol(\"WEIGHT\")  # array of float64 with shape [npol, nvis]\n",
    "flag = tb.getcol(\"FLAG\")  # array of bool with shape [npol, nchan, nvis]\n",
    "data = tb.getcol(\"CORRECTED_DATA\")  # array of complex128 with shape [npol, nchan, nvis]\n",
    "tb.close()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 31,
   "id": "d491e212",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.783333Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.782756Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.946594Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.946028Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# average the polarizations\n",
    "# https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weighted_arithmetic_mean\n",
    "data = np.sum(data * weight[:, np.newaxis, :], axis=0) / np.sum(weight, axis=0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 32,
   "id": "a07d9acc",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.950853Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:21.950274Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:22.009603Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:22.008586Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# flag the data if either polarization was flagged\n",
    "flag = np.any(flag, axis=0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 33,
   "id": "892bdfac",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:22.013587Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:22.013084Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:22.022162Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:22.021564Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# combine the weights across polarizations\n",
    "weight = np.sum(weight, axis=0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 34,
   "id": "404b7779",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:22.027268Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:22.026694Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:22.032198Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:22.031685Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Calculate the \"radial\" baseline\n",
    "uu, vv, ww = uvw\n",
    "qq = np.sqrt(uu ** 2 + vv ** 2)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 35,
   "id": "feff64ad",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:22.036172Z",

    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# calculate visibility amplitude and phase\n",
    "amp = np.abs(data)\n",
    "phase = np.angle(data)"
   ]

    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1, figsize=(3.5, 3.5))\n",

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8162d093",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Example Queries with ms tools\n",
    "Sometimes your measurement set might contain multiple spectral windows with different numbers of channels or polarizations. In such a situation, the above queries with the ``tb`` tool will most likely fail, because they are trying to read data with inherently different shapes into an array with one common shape. One solution is to use the [ms](https://casa.nrao.edu/casadocs-devel/stable/global-tool-list/tool_ms/methods) tool.\n",
    "\n",
    "The two most useful methods are ``ms.selectinit`` followed by ``ms.getdata``. The first earmarks a subset of data based upon the given ``DATA_DESC_ID``, the second returns the actual data. It is possible to retrieve the data from a single spectral window because all data within a given spectral window will have the same polarization and channelization setup. The downside is that if your dataset has multiple spectral windows, you will need to repeat the queries for each one. It isn't obvious that there is a faster way to retrieve the data in such a situation, however."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 37,
   "id": "e0dc0687",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:22.684341Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:22.683804Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:22.818911Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:22.819367Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "True"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 1,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "ms.open(fname)\n",
    "# select the spectral window\n",
    "ms.selectinit(datadescid=0)\n",
    "# query the desired columnames as a list\n",
    "query = ms.getdata([\"WEIGHT\", \"UVW\"])\n",
    "# always a good idea to reset the earmarked data\n",
    "ms.selectinit(reset=True)\n",
    "ms.close()"
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3f27eaa1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Putting it together to export visibilities\n",
    "This slightly larger example shows how to combine some of the above queries to read channel frequencies, baselines, and visibilites, and export them from the CASA environment saved as an ``*.npz`` file."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 40,
   "id": "94652697",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:22.838368Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:22.837850Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.113007Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.113415Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "True"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 1,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# query the data\n",
    "tb.open(fname)\n",
    "ant1 = tb.getcol(\"ANTENNA1\")  # array of int with shape [nvis]\n",
    "ant2 = tb.getcol(\"ANTENNA2\")  # array of int with shape [nvis]\n",
    "uvw = tb.getcol(\"UVW\")  # array of float64 with shape [3, nvis]\n",
    "weight = tb.getcol(\"WEIGHT\")  # array of float64 with shape [npol, nvis]\n",
    "flag = tb.getcol(\"FLAG\")  # array of bool with shape [npol, nchan, nvis]\n",
    "data = tb.getcol(\"CORRECTED_DATA\")  # array of complex128 with shape [npol, nchan, nvis]\n",
    "tb.close()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 41,
   "id": "46b12d76",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.118381Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.117395Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.121450Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.121899Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# get the channel information\n",
    "tb.open(fname + \"/SPECTRAL_WINDOW\")\n",
    "chan_freq = tb.getcol(\"CHAN_FREQ\")\n",
    "num_chan = tb.getcol(\"NUM_CHAN\")\n",
    "tb.close()\n",
    "chan_freq = chan_freq.flatten()  # Hz\n",
    "nchan = len(chan_freq)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7365cbe8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Check to make sure the channels are in blushifted to redshifted order, otherwise reverse channel order"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 42,
   "id": "e9acc6e3",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.127506Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.126255Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.128152Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.128624Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "if (nchan > 1) and (chan_freq[1] > chan_freq[0]):\n",
    "    # reverse channels\n",
    "    chan_freq = chan_freq[::-1]\n",
    "    data = data[:, ::-1, :]\n",
    "    flag = flag[:, ::-1, :]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "506fe6da",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Keep only the cross-correlation visibilities and throw out the auto-correlation visibilities (i.e., where ``ant1 == ant2``)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 43,
   "id": "45ede6ac",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.132910Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.132396Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.241997Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.240970Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "xc = np.where(ant1 != ant2)[0]\n",
    "data = data[:, :, xc]\n",
    "flag = flag[:, :, xc]\n",
    "uvw = uvw[:, xc]\n",
    "weight = weight[:, xc]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 44,
   "id": "0b6e3489",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.247164Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.246589Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.472571Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.473097Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# average the polarizations\n",
    "data = np.sum(data * weight[:, np.newaxis, :], axis=0) / np.sum(weight, axis=0)\n",
    "flag = np.any(flag, axis=0)\n",
    "weight = np.sum(weight, axis=0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 45,
   "id": "11b17ac5",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.478595Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.477745Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.480314Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.480756Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "(9, 325080)\n",
      "(9, 325080)\n",
      "(325080,)\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# After this step, ``data`` should be shape ``(nchan, nvis)`` and weights should be shape ``(nvis,)``\n",
    "print(data.shape)\n",
    "print(flag.shape)\n",
    "print(weight.shape)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 46,
   "id": "6ee85150",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.484534Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.483525Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.486658Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.486194Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# when indexed with mask, returns valid visibilities\n",
    "mask = ~flag"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 47,
   "id": "f3975e0e",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.490716Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.490134Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.520575Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.519852Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# convert uu and vv to kilolambda\n",
    "uu, vv, ww = uvw  # unpack into len nvis vectors\n",
    "# broadcast to the same shape as the data\n",
    "# stub to broadcast uu,vv, and weights to all channels\n",
    "broadcast = np.ones((nchan, 1))\n",
    "uu = uu * broadcast\n",
    "vv = vv * broadcast\n",
    "weight = weight * broadcast"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 48,
   "id": "e4730fd0",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.526357Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.524783Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.527179Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.527785Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# calculate wavelengths in meters\n",
    "wavelengths = c_ms / chan_freq[:, np.newaxis]  # m"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 49,
   "id": "cd59a4ba",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.531647Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.531065Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.559708Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.559172Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# calculate baselines in klambda\n",
    "uu = 1e-3 * uu / wavelengths  # [klambda]\n",
    "vv = 1e-3 * vv / wavelengths  # [klambda]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 50,
   "id": "b174f9a9",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.564648Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.563404Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.565411Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.565881Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "frequencies = chan_freq * 1e-9  # [GHz]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "60d61f32",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Since we have a multi-channel dataset, we need to make a decision about how to treat flagged visibilities. If we wanted to export only unflagged visibilities, there is a chance that some channels will have different number of flagged visibilities, which means we can no longer represent the data as a nicely packed, contiguous, rectangular array.\n",
    "\n",
    " Here, we sidestep this issue by just exporting *all* of the data (including flagged, potentially erroneous, visibilities), but, we also include the ``mask`` used to identify the valid visibilities. This punts on a final decision about how to store unflagged visibilities---the user will need to make sure that they correctly apply the mask when they load the data in a new environment."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 51,
   "id": "268b510a",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.570469Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.569879Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.787869Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-05-31T01:16:23.786937Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# save data to numpy file for later use\n",
    "np.savez(\n",
    "    \"visibilities.npz\",\n",
    "    frequencies=frequencies,  # [GHz]\n",
    "    uu=uu,  # [klambda]\n",
    "    vv=vv,  # [klambda]\n",
    "    weight=weight,  # [1/Jy^2]\n",
    "    data=data,  # [Jy]\n",
    "    mask=mask,  # [Bool]\n",
    ")"
   ]
  }
